# Every other text file in this repo is git-normalized to LF, matching
# Prettier's `endOfLine: "lf"` (prettier.config.js) and Node/TS's own
# indifference to line-ending style. Without this, a checkout on a machine
# with `core.autocrlf=true` (a common Windows default, including this repo's
# own local config) silently rewrites every LF blob to CRLF on disk — the
# blobs themselves stay pure LF, but `prettier --check` then reports every
# such file as "unformatted" purely from the line-ending mismatch, with zero
# actual content difference. Pinning `eol=lf` here makes checkout behavior
# identical on every machine and CI runner regardless of local autocrlf
# settings, so that class of false-positive drift cannot recur. The two
# overrides below remain the deliberate exceptions: they require the opposite
# (or platform-specific) ending because an interpreter, not a formatter,
# consumes them.
* text=auto eol=lf

# The hook-script templates are executed by an interpreter that does not
# tolerate the wrong line endings: cmd.exe parses a `.cmd` up to each CR (an
# LF-only file makes it run fragments of the comment block as commands), and a
# CRLF `.sh` makes the kernel look for an interpreter named `sh\r`. Pin both so
# a checkout under any `core.autocrlf` setting stores the right bytes.
#
# `renderHookScript` normalizes line endings again when it materializes a
# script, so a mangled checkout still produces a working hook — this file keeps
# the source of truth honest rather than being the only line of defense.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.sh  text eol=lf

# Golden fixtures capture renderHookScript's exact output bytes, including
# line endings, for tests/adapters/goldenFixtures.test.ts. The same
# autocrlf hazard applies: without pinning, a checkout could silently flip
# the fixture's line endings and the test would compare against the wrong
# bytes rather than catching a real regression.
tests/fixtures/hookScript/windows.cmd.golden text eol=crlf
tests/fixtures/hookScript/posix*.golden      text eol=lf
